# Grey Text on White/Light Backgrounds

Do not use grey text lighter than `gray-700` when the background is white or light (e.g. `bg-white`, `bg-gray-50`, `bg-gray-100`). Light grey on white is very hard to read.

## Rule

- **On white or light backgrounds**: Use at least `text-gray-700` for grey text. For placeholders, use at least `placeholder-gray-600`.
- **On contrasting backgrounds**: Grey text is fine when the background is dark or distinctly colored (e.g. dark mode `dark:text-gray-300` on dark bg, or text on `bg-gray-300`).

## Avoid

- `text-gray-300`, `text-gray-400`, `text-gray-500`, `text-gray-600` on white, gray-50, or gray-100
- `placeholder-gray-400` (or lighter) on white/light input backgrounds

## Use instead

- `text-gray-700` (or `text-gray-800` / `text-gray-900`) for body and secondary text on light backgrounds
- `placeholder-gray-600` or `placeholder-gray-700` for input placeholders on light backgrounds

## Tailwind examples

```html
<!-- ❌ BAD: light grey on white -->
<p class="text-gray-500">Hint text</p>
<nav class="... text-gray-400">Inactive link</nav>

<!-- ✅ GOOD: readable grey on white -->
<p class="text-gray-700">Hint text</p>
<nav class="... text-gray-700">Inactive link</nav>
```

Leave grey-on-contrasting-background (e.g. dark mode, or chips with `bg-gray-300`) unchanged.
